# UX Standards

Build experiences, not screens. Users should rarely stop to think.

## Before any feature

Who is the user? What is the goal? What is the fastest path? What confuses them? Can one step/click/field be removed?

## Cognitive load

Reduce thinking, memory, decisions, distractions. Increase clarity, feedback, confidence.

## Required states

Every meaningful surface needs:

- Loading (skeleton or spinner as appropriate)
- Empty (real empty — never fake demo rows in production)
- Error (what happened + how to recover + retry when possible)
- Success feedback (toast or inline)

## Flows

Clear start → progress → completion → recovery. Users always know where they are and what happens next.

## Recognition over recall

Prefer defaults, recent items, autocomplete, suggestions, templates. Do not force users to remember IDs or prior screens.

## Forgiveness

- Confirm destructive actions
- Preserve form input on error
- Undo/recover when feasible
- Never disable controls without explaining why

## Operator ease (ops products)

Cashiers, warehouse, HR, field staff need fewer clicks and less typing than admin power-users. Optimize the primary role's path first.
